  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's a lived reality for many who've seen their potential dimmed by the weight of societal expectations. As a practicing engineer in Chicago, I've witnessed firsthand how the idea that 'women aren't good at math' or 'people of color don't belong in engineering' can subtly undermine performance. When students from underrepresented groups hear these stereotypes, their focus shifts from learning to anxiety, which directly impacts their ability to solve problems. I've seen this in my own work with young engineers—those who internalize these beliefs often struggle to participate fully in team discussions, even when they have the skills. The question of whether we should address it is obvious: yes, absolutely. But the 'how' is where it gets nuanced. We need to move beyond surface-level awareness and create systemic change. In my community, we've started by integrating inclusive role models into our mentorship programs, showing students that diverse voices have shaped the field. We also emphasize growth mindset in our workshops, helping participants reframe challenges as opportunities rather than proof of inadequacy. This isn't about fixing people—it's about fixing the environment. And as someone who values practical, grounded solutions, I believe this approach aligns with the kind of thoughtful, community-driven work that can make a real difference in STEM education and careers.",
